'ZJ-001-063_Received_queue\', suggesting that services were unable to process incoming network packets, a classic sign of networ\nAffected Metrics: CPU, I/O, latency, network, packet loss, rr, rt, thread\nRoot Cause Category: The root cause of the incident was a network delay affecting node os_018 at 01:48:00. Evidence from the anomaly reports points to a broader network is\nFailure Pattern: The root cause of the incident was a network delay affecting node os_018 at 01:48:00. Evidence from the anomaly reports points to a broader network issue, indicated by an increase in received error packets on redis_010 and a buildup in the network receive queues on docker_001 and docker_007 at the exact time of the failure. On the affected node os_018, this network problem manifested as an anomalous increase in the total number of container threads, which is a typical symptom of processes blocking on network I/O. A drop in available CPU on os_018 a minute prior may have exacerbated the node\'s inability to process network traffic efficiently.\nMitigation Principles: 1. Enhance network monitoring on all nodes to include metrics for packet retransmissions, packet loss, and network interface errors to more quickly isolate the source of network degradation. 2. Investigate the cause of the CPU pressure on os_018 to ensure nodes have sufficient resources to handle both application logic and network I/O. 3. Configure alerting on critical network health indicators such as \'Received_errors_packets\' and sustained \'Received_queue\' growth to enable proactive response.\n\nBackgroud:\n"\n\n\nBased on this information, identify the MOST LIKELY root cause component and reason from the candidate list.\nFollow these rules:\n- The root cause must be a single component from the candidate list.\n- The reason must be directly supported by the anomaly description.\n- Assign a suspicious score between 0.0 and 1.0 (higher = more confident).\n\nRespond ONLY with a JSON object in this exact format:\n{